"Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Bunny, Basford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bunny with Bradmore, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bellers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Bellars  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bellairs","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Bellars  , suggesting French <i>belle(s) aire(s)</i> ‘lovely demeanor’."]},{"name":"Bellars","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English (Northamptonshire):","(of Norman origin): apparently from Old French <i>bélier</i> ‘ram’, hence a nickname for someone thought to resemble a ram in some way or possibly a metonymic occupational name for a shepherd. In Northamptonshire the name attracts excrescent <i>-s</i> already by 1377."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Roger De Bellers Of Bunny was born in 1270, in Bunny with Bradmore, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Bellers, was 18 and his mother, Amicia De Aungeville, was 14. He married Alice de Wakebridge in 1315, in Kirby Bellars, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1326, in Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1270–1326":"1270–1326","1273–1368":"1273–1368","1318–1367":"9.jaanuar1318kuni8.jaanuar1319–1367","1318–1380":"9.jaanuar1318kuni8.jaanuar1319–1380","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1256–Female":"1256–Surnud","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1368":"1368","1367":"1367","1256":"1256","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1270":"1270","1380":"1380","1318":"9. jaanuar 1318 kuni 8. jaanuar 1319","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kirby Bellars, Leicestershire, England":"Kirby Bellars, Leicestershire, England","Basford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Basford, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England","Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bunny, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bunny, Basford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bunny with Bradmore, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1270–1326":"1270–1326","1273–1368":"1273–1368","1318–1367":"vuodesta9.tammi